## Current Focus (2026-06-13 â€” Cycle 8 SOURCE TRACE DONE: the renderer A/B was a vsync CONFOUND) [SUPERSEDED by Cycle 9 â€” vsync REFUTED, renderer isolation now HARD]


**hypothesis (REFINED â€” falsifiable):** The view matrix and the entire scene transform are
IDENTICAL byte-for-byte between D3D9 and D3D11 â€” `Camera::applyState()`
(Camera.cpp:629-640) reads `getTransform_o2w()` at RENDER time and pushes one
`Graphics::setWorldToCameraTransform` for both renderers; the projection math (Camera.cpp:106-243)
is renderer-agnostic. So a renderer swap CANNOT change WHAT is presented at the portal frame â€”
it can only change HOW/WHEN it is presented. The Cycle-7 renderer A/B did NOT isolate "render
path"; it CONFLATED two variables:
  1. the rendering API (D3D9 vs D3D11), and
  2. the PRESENT/VSYNC CADENCE.
Hard source proof of the confound:
  - stage/client_d.cfg has `allowTearing=true` (:72) AND `windowed=true` (:44).
  - D3D9 honors it: Direct3d9.cpp:2253-2256 -> `allowTearing` -> `D3DPRESENT_INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE`
    = **VSYNC OFF, torn, uncapped present.**
  - D3D11 IGNORES it: Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137 hardcodes `ms_swapChain->Present(1, 0)`
    = **VSYNC ON (SyncInterval=1)** with `DXGI_SWAP_EFFECT_FLIP_DISCARD`, 2 buffers
    (Device.cpp:560-577). The inline comment says "vsync=1 for Wave 3 MVP (allowTearing override
    is Wave 4+)" â€” i.e. the D3D11 path has NOT yet wired up allowTearing.
So "Release+D3D9 snaps / Release+D3D11 hardly snaps" is most parsimoniously explained as
**vsync-OFF (tearing) makes a single transient one-frame portal-crossing frame visible, while
vsync-ON + the flip-model present queue paces/masks it.** This REFRAMES the bug: the snap is a
ONE-FRAME TRANSIENT (camera parent-cell flap world<->foyer1 every frame at the doorway, so
`getTransform_o2w()` resolves via two different cell paths on alternating frames) that is
PERCEPTUALLY AMPLIFIED by tearing/immediate present, NOT a renderer-specific transform error.

**WHY this matters:** before Cycle 8 the plan was to hunt a "render/camera-side fix" justified
by the A/B. That justification is now suspect â€” the A/B is not a clean isolation. Writing a
render-path fix on a confounded signal risks the same false-lock the two prior 3-AI consensus
rounds hit. The mechanism must be DISAMBIGUATED first with a one-variable experiment.

