## Evidence (continued â€” 2026-06-13 Cycle 8 render-side source trace)

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” View matrix is RENDERER-IDENTICAL.
  `Camera::applyState()` (Camera.cpp:629-640) reads `getTransform_o2w()` at RENDER time,
  inverts it to worldToCamera, and pushes ONE `Graphics::setWorldToCameraTransform` +
  `setProjectionMatrix` for both renderers. The projection matrix construction
  (Camera.cpp:106-243) is pure math, renderer-agnostic. `Camera::beginScene` (:652) just calls
  applyState then sets the ShaderPrimitiveSorter camera. There is NO per-renderer view/camera
  transform branch.
  implication: a renderer swap cannot change WHAT geometry/camera is presented at the portal
  frame â€” only HOW/WHEN. So the Cycle-7 A/B cannot, by itself, localize the snap to a
  "render path". It can only differ in present behavior.

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” The Cycle-7 renderer A/B was a VSYNC CONFOUND (hard source proof).
  stage/client_d.cfg: `allowTearing=true` (:72), `windowed=true` (:44).
  - D3D9 (Direct3d9.cpp:2253-2256): `if (getAllowTearing()) PresentationInterval =
    D3DPRESENT_INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE; else INTERVAL_ONE`. allowTearing=true -> IMMEDIATE ->
    **VSYNC OFF / torn / uncapped.** SwapEffect=COPY, BackBufferCount=1 (windowed).
  - D3D11 (Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137): hardcoded `ms_swapChain->Present(1, 0)` ->
    **VSYNC ON (SyncInterval=1)**; swap chain is `DXGI_SWAP_EFFECT_FLIP_DISCARD`, BufferCount=2
    (Device.cpp:560-577). Inline comment: "vsync=1 for Wave 3 MVP (allowTearing override is
    Wave 4+)" â€” the D3D11 path does NOT read allowTearing at all.
  implication: the two A/B runs differed in BOTH renderer API AND present cadence (D3D9 torn
  vsync-off vs D3D11 paced vsync-on flip-model). "D3D9 snaps / D3D11 hardly snaps" is therefore
  NOT clean evidence for a render-path bug. Most parsimonious read: a single transient
  portal-crossing frame is made visible by tearing/immediate present (D3D9) and paced/masked by
  vsync + the flip-model present queue (D3D11). The fix justification ("render/camera-side")
  rested on this A/B and is now suspect â€” must disambiguate before coding.

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” The renderer-INDEPENDENT source of a 1-frame transient.
  `FreeChaseCamera::alter` (FreeChaseCamera.cpp:604-651): every frame it sets the camera's parent
  cell to the target's cell (`if (getParentCell() != targetCell) setParentCell(targetCell)`),
  disables portal transitions, then `setTransform_o2p(targetObject->getTransform_o2c())` and
  re-enables transitions. So the camera's parent cell tracks the player's cell. The Cycle-6/7
  capture showed the chase cam (obj 0) flapping world<->foyer1 EVERY frame at the doorway.
  `Object::getTransform_o2w()` (Object.cpp:1418-1446) resolves o2w via
  `m_attachedToObject->getTransform_o2w() * m_objectToParent` when in a cell (attached), but
  returns `m_objectToParent` directly when in the world cell (not attached) â€” TWO DIFFERENT
  resolution paths that alternate as the camera's cell flaps. Door threshold world-Y ~5.1 vs
  outdoor terrain world-Y ~1.06 (~4 m). A frame where the camera resolves through the "other"
  cell yields a transiently different camera world position.
  implication: this is the only renderer-independent candidate ROOT for a 1-frame portal pop, and
  the only fix that would help BOTH renderers. But it is currently a HYPOTHESIS â€” the logged
  PLAYER position at the portal is clean (y=5.106, tiny segs); the camera (obj 0) flap is logged
  but the camera's resolved o2w per frame was NOT captured. Needs the disambiguation experiment
  before committing to a fix here.


