## Evidence (continued â€” 2026-06-13 Cycle 9 source trace: the paradox RESOLVED â€” timestep, not present)

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” applyState confirmed renderer-identical at the CURRENT paths.
  `Camera::applyState()` lives at `src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/shared/Camera.cpp:629-640`
  (NOT the clientGame path cited in Cycle 8 â€” same function, different file). It inverts
  `getTransform_o2w()` to worldToCamera and pushes ONE `Graphics::setWorldToCameraTransform` +
  `setProjectionMatrix` for BOTH renderers. Both plugins consume the same `Transform`:
  D3D9 `Direct3d9.cpp:3271 setWorldToCameraTransform`, D3D11
  `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1868 setWorldToCameraTransform`. The frame loop
  (`Game.cpp:1199-1228`) is single-threaded and renderer-agnostic: beginScene -> IoWinManager::draw
  (world draw via the camera) -> endScene -> present, in that fixed order regardless of plugin.
  implication: at a GIVEN frame with a GIVEN camera transform, both renderers draw the same scene
  from the same viewpoint. A renderer swap cannot, within one frame, change WHAT is drawn. So the
  Cycle-8 "renderer-identical view matrix" claim is CORRECT and STANDS. The paradox is real and
  must be resolved at the cross-FRAME (timestep) level, not the within-frame transform level.

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” THE RESOLUTION: the simulation timestep IS the per-frame present-bound
  wall-clock delta, so the renderer feeds back into the simulation.
  `Game::runGameLoop` reads `elapsedTime = Clock::frameTime()` (`Game.cpp:1092`) at the TOP of each
  frame and passes it to every `alter(elapsedTime)` â€” camera (`FreeChaseCamera::alter`), player
  controller, and collision. `Clock::frameTime()`/`Clock::update` (`Clock.cpp:226,235`) returns the
  QueryPerformanceCounter delta between successive frames â€” i.e. the WALL-CLOCK duration of the
  previous frame, INCLUDING how long `Graphics::present()` took. The two plugins present differently:
  D3D9 `INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE`/`INTERVAL_ONE` with SwapEffect=COPY, 1 backbuffer (`Direct3d9.cpp:2230,
  2253-2256`); D3D11 hardcoded `Present(1,0)` with `DXGI_SWAP_EFFECT_FLIP_DISCARD`, 2 buffers
  (`Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137`, Device.cpp:560-577). Different present model => different per-frame
  timing distribution => different `elapsedTime` stream => a DIFFERENT (but each internally valid)
  collision/portal/camera integration. This is the renderer-dependent channel that does NOT touch
  the view matrix. The simulation is NOT renderer-independent in practice: it is timestep-driven and
  the timestep is renderer-bound.
  implication: this is the ONLY mechanism by which the same single-threaded, renderer-agnostic draw
  path can produce a renderer-correlated visible snap. The snap is a TIMESTEP-SENSITIVE transient in
  the camera/collision integration, modulated by each plugin's present pacing.

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” THE SMOKING GUN already in the Cycle-9 runs, previously overlooked:
  D3D9 vsync-ON (Run B) snaps 8/10 â€” MORE than D3D9 vsync-OFF (Run A) 6/10. If the snap were a
  present-CADENCE/tearing artifact (a transient made visible by torn immediate present), vsync-OFF
  would show it MORE, not less. It shows LESS. So steadier/larger frame pacing INCREASES the snap.
  That is a TIMESTEP signature, not a present-visibility signature: vsync-ON yields a larger, more
  uniform ~16.6 ms `frameTime`; vsync-OFF yields shorter, more variable timesteps. A larger timestep
  means the player controller integrates a bigger per-frame move into/along the doorway geometry, so
  the collision penetration (and therefore the resolveCollisions resetPos rewind magnitude â€” the
  documented frame-7593 4 m vertical pop) is larger and more likely to be perceptible. D3D11's
  flip-model present produces yet another timing profile that, in Kenny's runs, lands the timestep
  where the transient does not occur / is sub-perceptual (0/10).
  implication: the renderer A/B IS real and IS hard â€” but it isolates the snap to the renderer's
  PRESENT-TIMING effect on the simulation TIMESTEP, NOT to the render/draw/view path. The
  "render-side artifact" framing from Cycles 7-8 is too narrow: the renderer is upstream of the
  simulation via Clock::frameTime, so a "D3D9 render-path artifact" is really a
  "D3D9-present-timing-driven timestep that exercises a pre-existing timestep-fragile transient."

- timestamp: 2026-06-13 â€” reconciling with Cycle 3 (the "frame-rate disproven" result).
  Cycle 3 capped FPS globally (NVIDIA 30 vs 250) and saw "maybe a little better, not sure" â€” read at
  the time as disproving timestep-fragility. But a global FPS CAP changes the AVERAGE timestep; it
  does not reproduce the per-frame timestep DISTRIBUTION + jitter that a present-model swap produces,
  and it does not change the present-queue depth (D3D9 1-deep COPY vs D3D11 2-deep FLIP_DISCARD) that
  shifts WHICH integrated frame is on screen at the portal-cross instant. The Cycle-3 null result is
  therefore NOT in conflict with a timestep mechanism: the snap is sensitive to the timestep at the
  exact 1-2 portal-crossing frames (a transient), not to steady-state average FPS. This also explains
  the long-standing non-determinism (snaps "sometimes"): it depends on where the variable timestep
  boundary lands relative to the player's penetration of the doorway plane that frame.

## Eliminated

- hypothesis: DPVS occlusion culling causing the snap.
  reason: `portalRecusionDepth` unchanged in Phase 10 work; cell-portal
  traversal is orthogonal to the `OCCLUSION_CULLING` bit modified at
  `RenderWorld.cpp:909/913`. Snap predates Phase 10 by a week.

- hypothesis: DbgHelp callstack lookup overhead.
  reason: `lookUpCallStackNames=false` already disabled in
  `client_d.cfg:79`. Not the bottleneck.

- hypothesis: Phase 10 edits introduced the regression.
  reason: First regressed build (`build-v145/`) dated 2026-05-08, one week
  before Phase 10 D-13/D-14 commits.

- hypothesis: The same-frame portal cell ping-pong (Aâ†’Bâ†’A re-entrant
  positionChanged) is the cause, fixable by a frame-scoped reversal guard in
  CellProperty::positionChanged.
  reason: FALSIFIED 2026-06-13 by runtime capture. The "reversed" 2nd portal
  segment is the legitimate collision correction (1st segment overshoots the
  portal plane; 2nd corrects back to the side where the final position is).
  Built the guard (7820aea50), tested gl05, REVERTED it (a6df32348): suppressing
  the correction pinned cell membership on the overshoot side while the body sat
  on the corrected side â†’ portal renderer culled the wrong cell â†’ cantina interior
  dropped to the skybox + snap on exit. Left alone, both segments apply and
  membership tracks position (self-correcting). CORNERSNAP-CELLJUMP = 0 all session
  â†’ net cell change was always correct; the snap was never a cell-membership bug.
  Do NOT re-attempt portal-side suppression.

- hypothesis: resolveCollisions resetPos rewind (H1 bad-live-Y OR H2 mis-anchored-reset)
  is the cause of the EVERY-EXIT cantina snap.
  reason: ELIMINATED 2026-06-13 (Cycle 7). The player's no-wall-bump exits produced ZERO
  CORNERSNAP-RESETSRC lines â€” resolveCollisions only fires on a resolved collision, so the
  every-exit snap is collision-INDEPENDENT and cannot originate in resolveCollisions. The
  RESETSRC probe captured an NPC (obj 1107534696, isValid() lets NPCs through), whose rows
  showed liveW_y == pointA_worldY (dY=0) on every frame â€” no divergence for either H1 or H2.
  The logged player PORTAL crossings are clean (y=5.106, tiny segs, no teleport). DECISIVE:
  renderer A/B â€” Release+D3D9 (no instrumentation) snaps; Release+D3D11 (no instrumentation)
  "hardly any snap". A renderer swap cannot change the collision/portal simulation â†’ the snap
  is render/camera-presentation, not collision response. NOTE: the SEPARATE frame-7593 4 m
  wall-graze rewind is a real (distinct) collision event, not the every-exit snap.

