## Cycle 9 â€” RENDERER ISOLATION HARD; paradox resolved via source (2026-06-13)

Goal: find_root_cause_only (NO fix). Three-run controlled isolation (Run A/B/C above)
refuted vsync (M1) and the build axis, leaving the renderer plugin as the sole variable.
gsd-debugger resolved the Cycle-8 paradox by source analysis.

**ROOT CAUSE (file:line, falsifiable):** a pre-existing **timestep-fragile one-frame
collision-rewind transient** at the cantina doorway portal, **MODULATED (not caused) by the
renderer's present timing**. The view matrix and draw path ARE genuinely renderer-identical
(Cycle-8 claim STANDS); the renderer reaches the simulation through a back channel â€” the
simulation TIMESTEP.

- Within a frame, the draw is renderer-agnostic: `Camera::applyState()`
  (`src/engine/client/library/clientGraphics/src/shared/Camera.cpp:629-640` â€” corrected path;
  prior cycles cited a non-existent clientGame path) pushes ONE shared
  `Graphics::setWorldToCameraTransform` + `setProjectionMatrix`; both plugins consume the
  identical Transform (D3D9 `Direct3d9.cpp:3271`, D3D11 `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:1868`). The
  frame loop (`Game.cpp:1199-1228`) is single-threaded. A renderer swap cannot change WHAT is
  drawn in a frame.
- The renderer-dependent channel is `elapsedTime = Clock::frameTime()` (`Game.cpp:1092`) â€” the
  QPC wall-clock duration of the PREVIOUS frame INCLUDING `Graphics::present()`
  (`Clock.cpp:226,235`). It drives every `alter(elapsedTime)` (camera, controller, collision).
  D3D9 (COPY, 1 backbuffer, INTERVAL_IMMEDIATE|ONE, `Direct3d9.cpp:2230/2253-2256`) vs D3D11
  (FLIP_DISCARD, 2 buffers, `Present(1,0)`, `Direct3d11_Device.cpp:1137`, Device.cpp:560-577)
  present with different models -> different per-frame timestep distributions -> the
  timestep-driven integration lands the portal transient differently.
- The visible transient itself: at the doorway graze crossing foyer1<->world,
  `CollisionResolve::resolveCollisions` rewinds to `resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(m_cellB)`
  (`CollisionResolve.cpp:320`, applied :337) = start-of-timestep pos transformed into the
  now-current cell -> pops world-Y ~4 m (interior floor ~5.1 vs terrain ~1.06). Rewind magnitude
  scales with penetration depth = velocity x elapsedTime. Larger/steadier timestep -> deeper
  penetration -> bigger, more perceptible rewind.

**SMOKING GUN already in the Cycle-9 runs:** D3D9 vsync-ON (Run B) snaps 8/10 > D3D9 vsync-OFF
(Run A) 6/10. A present-cadence/tearing artifact would be WORSE with vsync OFF; it is worse with
the LARGER, STEADIER vsync-ON timestep -> a TIMESTEP signature, not a present-visibility one. This
independently refutes the Cycle-8 "tearing amplifies the transient" reframe for the right reason,
and reconciles Cycle-3's FPS-cap null (a global cap changes average timestep, not the per-frame
distribution/jitter nor the present-queue depth at the 1-2 portal frames -> also explains the
long-standing non-determinism).

**FIX-vs-ACCEPT framing (for Kenny):**
- ACCEPT D3D11 (recommended, zero code change): rasterMajor=11 is the default/shipping renderer
  and is snap-free (0/10 + Release+D3D11 prior). Its 2-deep FLIP_DISCARD vsync cadence yields a
  timestep under which the doorway rewind never reaches visible magnitude. "Immune" by timing, not
  correctness â€” but shipping the renderer that does not surface the transient is a legitimate
  HARD-02 resolution.
- FIX the engine (higher-risk, helps both renderers): make the portal-crossing rewind
  timestep-independent OR constrain it to lateral-only when m_cellA != m_cellB at a portal plane
  (`CollisionResolve.cpp:320`). Touches SHARED collision response (all objects); risks regressing
  legitimate wall-sliding. The reverted ping-pong guard (a6df32348) shows portal-side suppression
  is hazardous. NOT the renderer or the camera.

**OPTIONAL TIGHT runtime confirmation (not required to arbitrate; only if Kenny wants the timestep
channel proven live before deciding):** add an additive `_DEBUG` one-liner logging `elapsedTime`
(`Clock::frameTime()`) alongside the existing CORNERSNAP-RESOLVE line; build Debug; run identical
