## Cycle 11 â€” WHY nailed (source-confirmed), minimal fix designed + implemented (2026-06-13)

### THE PRECISE FALSIFIABLE WHY (option 3: correct-but-undesirable height restore)

`resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(m_cellB) = CollisionUtils::transformToCell(m_cellA=lastCell,
m_pointA=lastPos_p, m_cellB=currentParentCell)` (CollisionResolve.cpp:320 -> :40-43 -> :1589).

The transform is ARITHMETICALLY CORRECT. It is NOT a stale-anchor bug (not H2) and NOT a wrong
transformToCell world-Y. It is OPTION 3 from the mandate: a **correct-but-undesirable restore of a
pre-crossing height**. Source proof:

1. `m_cellA / m_pointA` come from `colliderA->getLastCell() / getLastPos_p()`
   (CollisionResolve.cpp:267-268). `getLastPos_p()` is set by `storePosition()`
   (CollisionProperty.cpp:1169-1172 -> `setLastPos(getCell(), getTransform_o2p())`), captured at the
   END of the PREVIOUS `updateStep` (CollisionWorld.cpp:921). So at the portal-crossing frame,
   `m_pointA` is the player's settled position one frame ago, **on the interior foyer1 floor**
   (foyer1-local Y ~0.1, which is world-Y ~5.1). `m_cellA = foyer1`.
2. The player has since legitimately walked OUT the door. `m_cellB = world`, and the live position
   (`m_pointB = getPosition_p()`) is now on the **terrain** (world-Y ~1.06).
3. `transformToCell(foyer1, interior-floor-point, world)` faithfully produces world-Y ~5.1 â€” the
   pre-crossing interior-floor height expressed in world coords. `setPosition_p(resetPos)` (:366)
   then pops the object back UP ~4 m for one frame. THAT is the visible snap. (HARD numbers,
   frame 7593: live (â€¦,1.063,â€¦) -> resetPos (â€¦,5.100,â€¦).)

WHY this is undesirable rather than correct: **collision in this engine is FUNDAMENTALLY HORIZONTAL.**
`CollisionWorld::update:633` does `delta.y = 0.0f` on the move delta; `findContactWithFloor:762`
zeroes `delta.y`; the resolved waypoints (`positions`) and the resetPos rewind exist ONLY to restore
the **lateral (XZ)** start-of-timestep position so the XZ collision sweep can be replayed
(`moveObjectAlong`, :368). Vertical placement is owned by floor-snapping
(`Footprint::snapObjectToGround`, called in the post-rewind loop CollisionWorld.cpp:774-784), NOT by
the move/rewind. So carrying the cross-cell Y delta into `resetPos` is an **unwanted side effect** of
reusing a full 3D point transform for what is conceptually a 2D (XZ) rewind. At a portal whose two
cells' floors are coplanar (interior sub-cells foyer1/foyer2/cantina) the Y delta is ~0 and invisible;
at the main door (~4 m floor step) it is the snap. This exactly matches Run D (interior clean, door
snaps) and the Cycle-9 timestep modulation (bigger timestep -> deeper penetration -> resolve fires ->
rewind applied -> pop).

FALSIFICATION TEST (what would prove this WRONG): if, at the door-crossing resolve frame, the live
world-Y (`m_pointB` transformed to world) were ALSO ~5.1 (i.e. the player had NOT descended and the
rewind were merely restoring the true current height), the fix below would REINTRODUCE a snap by
forcing a wrong (terrain) Y. The frame-7593 capture refutes that: live world-Y was 1.063 (descended),
resetPos was 5.100 (pre-crossing). The Y the player legitimately holds at the resolve instant is the
descended one; the rewind overrides it.

### reasoning_checkpoint
```yaml
reasoning_checkpoint:
  hypothesis: "At a portal crossing (m_cellA != m_cellB), resolveCollisions rewinds the object to
    resetPos = the start-of-timestep position transformed into the current cell. That transform
    faithfully carries the PRE-CROSSING floor height (interior foyer1 ~5.1) even though the player
    has legitimately descended to terrain (~1.06). Applying it via setPosition_p pops world-Y ~4 m
    for one frame = the visible snap. The rewind only needs the LATERAL (XZ) start position; the Y
    component is an unwanted side effect because engine collision is XZ-only and floor-snapping owns Y."
  confirming_evidence:
    - "CollisionWorld::update:633 delta.y=0.0f and findContactWithFloor:762 delta.y=0 â€” move/collision is XZ-only by construction"
    - "Frame-7593 HARD capture: live world-Y 1.063 (descended to terrain) vs resetPos 5.100 (pre-crossing interior floor) â€” a 4.037 m vertical pop on a near-horizontal wall graze"
    - "resetPos source traced: m_pointA = getLastPos_p() settled on foyer1 floor last frame (CollisionProperty.cpp:1169-1172, storePosition at end of prior updateStep CollisionWorld.cpp:921); m_cellB = world now; transformToCell preserves the interior-floor world height"
    - "Run D: interior sub-cells (coplanar floors, ~0 Y step) clean; only the ~4 m main-door step still snaps â€” exactly what a cross-cell Y-delta-in-rewind predicts"
    - "Post-rewind snapObjectToGround loop (CollisionWorld.cpp:774-784) re-establishes the correct Y after the resolve â€” confirming the rewind's Y is throwaway and only XZ matters"
  falsification_test: "If the live world-Y at the resolve frame equaled the rewound resetPos world-Y (player NOT descended), preserving live-Y would inject a wrong height and CAUSE a snap. Frame-7593 (live 1.063 != resetPos 5.100) refutes this; runtime door-cross under the fix must show NO downward pop and correct landing."
  fix_rationale: "Scope the change to ONLY the cross-cell portal case (m_cellA != m_cellB). Replace the rewind's vertical component with the object's LIVE world-Y (the height the player legitimately holds), keeping the lateral XZ rewind intact so the collision replay still works. This removes the cross-cell Y reintroduction without touching same-cell rewinds (stairs/ramps/slopes/jumps all resolve within ONE cell, m_cellA==m_cellB, untouched) and without touching lateral wall-sliding (XZ rewind preserved). Floor-snapping continues to own final Y as before."
  blind_spots: "Multi-cell POBs (ships/turbolifts) where two connected cells have a deliberate vertical floor step that the player SHOULD traverse via the portal â€” but those are handled by floor-snap after the rewind, and the live-Y we preserve is the post-descent height, so the player keeps the height they actually reached. Vertical portals (a hatch/ladder where the legit move IS vertical across the portal) are the main risk; mitigated because we keep LIVE Y (where the player actually is), not a forced terrain Y. Need Kenny's regression spot-checks (another door, a multi-level POB) to confirm."
```

### FIX DESIGN (minimal, cross-cell-portal-scoped)

Location: CollisionResolve.cpp, immediately after `Vector resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(moveSeg.m_cellB);`
(:320), before the `setPosition_p(resetPos)` at :366.

Change: when `moveSeg.m_cellA != moveSeg.m_cellB` (a portal was crossed during the timestep), overwrite
the VERTICAL component of `resetPos` with the object's CURRENT (live) height, expressed in the current
cell frame â€” i.e. keep the lateral (XZ) rewind that collision needs, but do not drag the object back to
the pre-crossing floor height. Same-cell rewinds (m_cellA == m_cellB) are left byte-for-byte unchanged,
so all in-cell vertical collision response (stairs, ramps, slopes, jump/land) is untouched.

Implementation: the object is currently at `m_pointB = objectA->getPosition_p()` in `m_cellB` (the
current cell) â€” that is the live, legitimately-descended position. Its Y in the current cell frame is
`objectA->getPosition_p().y`. So:

```cpp
Vector resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(moveSeg.m_cellB);

// Cantina/portal corner-snap fix: collision rewind is conceptually LATERAL (XZ) only â€”
// CollisionWorld::update zeroes delta.y and floor-snapping owns vertical placement. When the
// object crossed a portal during this timestep (m_cellA != m_cellB), the start-of-timestep anchor
// (m_pointA, on the PRIOR cell's floor) transforms into the current cell carrying the PRE-CROSSING
// floor height, popping world-Y by the inter-cell floor step (~4 m at the Mos Eisley cantina main
// door). Preserve the object's LIVE current-cell height for the rewind so the lateral collision
// replay still runs but the cross-cell vertical discontinuity is not reintroduced. Same-cell
// rewinds (stairs/ramps/slopes/jumps) are unaffected.
if (moveSeg.m_cellA != moveSeg.m_cellB)
{
    resetPos.y = objectA->getPosition_p().y;
}
```

Why current-cell Y is the right vertical anchor: at the resolve site the object's parent cell is
`m_cellB` and its `getPosition_p()` is in that same frame, so `.y` is directly comparable to
`resetPos` (also in `m_cellB` frame). No transform needed. The subsequent `moveObjectAlong` replay and
`snapObjectToGround` loop then settle the final position exactly as before, just starting from the
correct (non-popped) height.

### DIFF APPLIED

`src/engine/shared/library/sharedCollision/src/shared/core/CollisionResolve.cpp`, in
`resolveCollisions(colliderA, moveSeg, colliderList)` RR_Resolved branch, immediately after
`Vector resetPos = moveSeg.getBegin(moveSeg.m_cellB);` (was :320) and before the `#ifdef _DEBUG`
CORNERSNAP instrumentation blocks (which were left byte-for-byte intact):

```cpp
		if (moveSeg.m_cellA != moveSeg.m_cellB)
		{
			resetPos.y = objectA->getPosition_p().y;
		}
```

(plus a multi-line explanatory comment above it). `objectA` is in scope (:286); `getPosition_p()` is
the same accessor already used to set `moveSeg.m_pointB` at :270. No header / struct / ABI change â€”
pure `.cpp` body edit, so gl07_r.dll stays ABI-paired with SwgClient_r without a renderer rebuild.
Koogie's committed CORNERSNAP-RESOLVE/CELLJUMP and the uncommitted CORNERSNAP-RESETSRC probe are
untouched.

